40|$|This {{dissertation}} develops and {{explores the}} methodology {{for the use}} of cubic <b>spline</b> <b>functions</b> in assessing time-by-covariate interactions in Cox proportional hazards regression models. These interactions indicate violations of the proportional hazards assumption of the Cox model. Use of cubic <b>spline</b> <b>functions</b> allows for the investigation of the shape of a possible covariate time-dependence without having to specify a particular functional form. Cubic <b>spline</b> <b>functions</b> yield both a graphical method and a formal test for the proportional hazards assumption as well as a test of the nonlinearity of the time-by-covariate interaction. Five existing methods for assessing violations of the proportional hazards assumption are reviewed and applied along with cubic splines to three well known two-sample datasets. An additional dataset with three covariates is used to explore the use of cubic <b>spline</b> <b>functions</b> in a more general setting. ...|$|R
